      <p>
        <term>Learning Point.</term>
      </p>

      <p>
        Part of a number line that satisfies two linear inequalities is the illustration of a given compound inequality.
      </p>

      <example>

        <statement>

          <p>
            Illustrate the compound inequality <m>4 &lt; y &lt; 8</m> on a number line.
          </p>

        </statement>

        <solution>

          <p>
            The compound inequality <m>4 &lt; y &lt; 8</m> can be split into two simple inequalities: <m>y &gt; 4</m> and <m>y &lt; 8</m>. To illustrate this on a number line, draw open circles at <m>4</m> and <m>8</m>.
          </p>

        <image>
          <shortdescription>numberline with shaded region in between</shortdescription>

        <latex-image>
          \begin{tikzpicture}
            % Draw number line with arrows on both ends
            \draw[thick, ->] (1,0) -- (9,0);
            
            % Draw tick marks on the number line
            \foreach \x in {2,3,4,5,6,7,8} {
                \draw[thick] (\x,0.1) -- (\x,-0.1);
            }
            
            % Draw open circles on x=2 and x=8 (on the number line)
            \draw (2,0) circle (5pt);
            \draw (8,0) circle (5pt);
            
            % Draw shaded region between 2 and 8 on the number line
            \draw[thick] (2,0) -- (8,0);
            \fill[black, opacity=0.7] (2,-0.1) rectangle (8,0.1);
            
            % Label points
            \foreach \x in {2,3,4,5,6,7,8} {
                \node[below] at (\x,0) {\x};
            }
            
          \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
          
        </image>

        </solution>

      </example>

